<p>The U.S. Federal Aviation Administration issued a notice on Friday warning pilots and airlines to exercise caution when flying over Venezuela due to a “worsening security situation” and heightened military activity, saying threats could pose risks at all altitudes [straitstimes.com#1][japantoday.com#1][aljazeera.com#1][scmp.com#1]. The advisory comes amid escalating tensions and an expanded U.S. military presence in the region, including deployment of the Navy’s largest aircraft carrier, additional warships, and F-35 aircraft, as President Trump has increased pressure on Venezuela [washingtonpost.com#1][scmp.com#1][firstpost.com#1].</p><img src='https://kagiproxy.com/img/_ALj1F9EeOSv_3_zZ80qWCSx0rKeuIZPRKyqU46CMcitwqC6_c2DfjME6SXriIB7BNO4TYITvEyUImppoxc_k_u_slavyVjPPIlQRq2p-S7Xv4AX91C6blKdZgxdD24WAF0xYPQaHQQeuUcWnu2i8LhSzNlIKcdlyEuqJ_I1Zqr88XsBSEKEsFVOxFTgLzcUHoiwDTU' alt='FAA warns of potential hazards in Venezuelan airspace amid heightened military activity' /><br /><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>FAA caution: The FAA flagged a “potentially hazardous situation” over Venezuela and urged pilots to “exercise caution” [straitstimes.com#1][japantoday.com#1][scmp.com#1]</li><li>Risk scope: The notice said threats could pose risks for aircraft “at all altitudes” [scmp.com#1]</li><li>Military buildup: Reports note a recent U.S. military buildup in the region, including the Navy’s largest aircraft carrier, at least eight other warships, and F-35 aircraft [scmp.com#1][firstpost.com#1]</li><li>Political context: The warning follows escalating tensions as President Trump has ramped up pressure on Venezuela and increased U.S. military presence in the area [washingtonpost.com#1]</li><li>Who is affected: The alert was directed broadly at pilots and major airlines operating in airspace over Venezuela [japantoday.com#1][straitstimes.com#1]</li></ul><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>U.S. Federal Aviation Administration: The FAA urges pilots to exercise caution over Venezuela due to a wo